<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870729-0043 </DOCNO><HL> Boeing's Lines of BusinessAs of December 31, 1986</HL><DD> 07/29/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> BACOMPUTERS (EDP)ELECTRIC, ELECTRONICS, APPLIANCES (ELE)AEROSPACE (ARO) </IN><TEXT>   These are Boeing Co.'s year-end 1986 lines of business:    Commercial aircraft: 60%. Boeing's current backlog is $22.5 billion. The company is bringing out derivatives of two of its hottest-selling aircraft, the 737 and the 747, and it faces a decision this year on whether to go ahead with plans to develop a new-technology airplane, the 7J7. It faces strong competition from Airbus Industrie, the European consortium.    Military aircraft: 30%. Many of Boeing's programs, such as the advanced tactical aircraft, are in the development phase, and tighter Pentagon procurement rules apply. Boeing recently won contracts to sell airborne warning and control system reconaissance planes to the British and French and to upgrade electronics on the U.S. Navy's P-3 reconaissance plane.    Missiles and space: 7%. Boeing recently won contracts for the Short Range Attack Missile, the submarine-launched Sea Lance missile and a mobile missile launcher. Boeing is competing to design systems for the manned space station.    Computing, electronics and other programs: 3%. Boeing recently announced the acquisition of ARGOSystems Inc., a defense electronics company based in Sunnyvale, Calif. Boeing has teamed with American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co. to compete for a $4.5 billion contract to build a new telephone system for the federal government. </TEXT></DOC>